{"type":"message","id":"3d8355ba","parentId":"138f2c07","timestamp":"2026-04-01T04:15:48.885Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"OK interesting. The creds.json is actually *valid* JSON with all the expected fields — `me.id: 6281938953639:12@s.whatsapp.net`, `registrationId: 22`, properly structured. The \"corruption\" detection might be a false positive, or it's a race condition where the file gets briefly truncated during writes.\n\nThe real issue is the **status 499** loop. Status 499 in WhatsApp Web context usually means the connection was closed by the *client* side — not by WhatsApp servers. This could be:\n\n1. A write race corrupting the creds mid-write (gateway writing + backup restoring simultaneously)\n2. WhatsApp server-side throttling this number due to too many rapid reconnects  \n3. A bug in the reconnect logic creating a self-perpetuating cycle\n\nLet me try a gateway restart to break the cycle:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"tooluse_yBi3lSb0iYIFqRu0K5xpCY","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"# First check if we've seen this before in memory\ncat /home/openclaw/.openclaw/workspace/memory/2026-03-31.md 2>/dev/null | grep -i \"whatsapp\\|499\\|flap\\|disconnect\" | head -10; echo \"===\"; cat /home/openclaw/.openclaw/workspace/memory/2026-04-01.md 2>/dev/null | head -20","timeout":5}}],"api":"bedrock-converse-stream","provider":"amazon-bedrock","model":"us.anthropic.claude-opus-4-6-v1","usage":{"input":1,"output":369,"cacheRead":73968,"cacheWrite":977,"totalTokens":75315,"cost":{"input":0.000005,"output":0.009225,"cacheRead":0.036983999999999996,"cacheWrite":0.0061062500000000006,"total":0.05232025}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775016939366}}
