{"type":"message","id":"cc010845","parentId":"1f8d94a1","timestamp":"2026-04-01T04:16:22.239Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"OK — the gateway is a child of the `openclaw` supervisor process (pid 1067463). I can't easily restart just the WhatsApp connection without restarting the whole gateway. But actually, the right approach might be simpler.\n\nThe issue is clear: WhatsApp creds corruption → 499 disconnect → restore from backup → reconnect → creds corrupt again → infinite loop. It's been going on since ~00:34 UTC today (4+ hours). The tight 60-second loop started around 02:17.\n\nThis is a known pattern with Baileys-based WhatsApp connections — the session can get into a death spiral where the creds file gets written mid-read/write. But since the creds themselves seem valid (I verified the JSON), the \"corruption\" might be a file-locking issue.\n\nIt's 12:14 AM WITA — deep quiet hours. The loop isn't *harmful* per se (WhatsApp is reconnecting and messages would still go through briefly each cycle), but it's wasting CPU cycles and log space. Not urgent enough to wake Lucy or do a risky gateway restart at night.\n\nLet me log this and move on:"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"tooluse_DYS2dG48QI9Pt794FHRT5n","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"cat /home/openclaw/.openclaw/workspace/memory/2026-04-01.md 2>/dev/null | head -5","timeout":5}}],"api":"bedrock-converse-stream","provider":"amazon-bedrock","model":"us.anthropic.claude-opus-4-6-v1","usage":{"input":1,"output":361,"cacheRead":76976,"cacheWrite":516,"totalTokens":77854,"cost":{"input":0.000005,"output":0.009025,"cacheRead":0.038488,"cacheWrite":0.003225,"total":0.050743}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1775016971783}}
