ths before the rest of the people catch on to this 03:09Yeah 03:16So, if people look at this part where you just send a message, goes to ClawdBot, comes back with an action, you might be like, okay, well, this Voiceflow thing from two years ago does the same thing 03:22But there's a big difference between this and Voiceflow because the TLDDR is, like I said, it is the air traffic control 03:28So, any channel you want 03:31You don't have to do anything fancy 03:32Everything comes out of the box, and this is fully open source 03:34Meaning, if you want to change what it can or can't do, or add a different connector, you don't have to wait for a platform to do it for you 03:42You can do it yourself 03:44And in terms of the tools, it comes with a series of skills 03:46Like, it already knows how to write Apple notes if you give it its own desktop 03:50It can create all kinds of 11 Labs voices and clones 03:52And a lot of these things that I'm mentioning in passing were huge edit workflows just four or five months ago, and now it's all natural language based 04:01And the fact that you can even make Claude modular, like essentially, let's say Claude is out of reach financially, either for you or your clients 04:11You can run a local model and then have that hooked up to this Claudebot brain, and Claude's just the orchestrator 04:18The Claudebot just decides what happens when, which tools are used, and which skills are needed 04:22Yeah, I mean, the the quickest thing you could do to cut your cost is jump over to some of the, the Google models, you know, like go from using Opus 4.5 to anything in the Google suite 04:30Uh, far, far cheaper than, uh, than the Anthropic ones 04:33So there's that 04:35Or, I mean, if you're really trying to minimize cost, it would be the Google side, right? Rather than having to purchase the Mac Mini and run the, run the stuff locally 04:42I tried to, uh, I tried to run, I can't remember what it is, O Lama, um, and get it to do a run claw code for me 04:49and I've got a pretty decent Mac, and it was just like it took 40 minutes to generate like 3,500 tokens or something 04:56So yeah, there is definitely a hardware limitation, so people need to be aware of that 04:59Yeah, it's a good segue 05:02So the ways you can use and set up ClawdBot, like we said, you don't need a Mac Mini 05:06The TLDDR of why people like myself have gone one is if you want to have that interface where you can physically see that your agent or agents have their own workspace, their own desktop where it can build, manage files, operate its own environment fully, but you want to separate it from your Mac and your life so you don't risk hackers, viruses, all kinds of things going wrong 05:30That's where the Mac Mini is becoming helpful 05:33And also, if you want to use open-source models, like Liam said, my computer basically nukes itself if it tries to run something on Olama 05:40So, because it's a virgin, blank slate, technically computer of its own, you can also run language models a lot more easily 05:46But for most of your audience, the cloud is probably one of the best places to go 05:53You can literally use Amazon Web Services 05:54There's tons of tutorials already on this, and you can hook it up on the free tier, and you can use this on the free tier 06:00It just might not be as pretty and cute as me, what I'm about to show your audience shortly in terms of how I have it set up 06:06>> Love it 06:12So, what you've got, what maybe 10, 20 bucks a month, or we talking like 50, 100 bucks a month to actually run this at any kind of, uh, kind of scale 06:18This literally free tier, like you can live on the free tier, depending on how much you use it 06:22I suppose it's if you're choosing to use the like the Gemini API, like accessing it through a hosted model, like, not a self-hosted model, but a provider where they're already running the models for you, and then you're just paying for the, uh, cloud space to be able to run the ClawdBot 